### Tailwind with React

Use `className` (not `class`) to apply Tailwind utilities:

```jsx
export default function Button({ children, variant = 'primary' }) {
  return (
    <button className={`
      px-6 py-2 rounded-lg font-semibold transition-colors
      ${variant === 'primary' 
        ? 'bg-blue-600 text-white hover:bg-blue-700' 
        : 'bg-gray-200 text-gray-800 hover:bg-gray-300'
      }
    `}>
      {children}
    </button>
  )
}
```

### Tailwind with Vue

Use `class` binding with objects or arrays:

```vue
<template>
  <button 
    :class="[
      'px-6 py-2 rounded-lg font-semibold',
      {
        'bg-blue-600 text-white hover:bg-blue-700': primary,
        'bg-gray-200 text-gray-800 hover:bg-gray-300': !primary,
      }
    ]"
  >
    <slot />
  </button>
</template>
```

### Tailwind with Next.js

Next.js has first-class support for Tailwind:

```bash
npx create-next-app@latest my-app --tailwind
```

The `app/globals.css` file already includes Tailwind directives:

```css
@tailwind base;
@tailwind components;
@tailwind utilities;
```

### Tailwind with Angular

Use `ngClass` or `class` binding:

```typescript
// component.ts
@Component({
  selector: 'app-button',
  template: `
    <button [ngClass]="[
      'px-6 py-2 rounded-lg font-semibold transition',
      primary ? 'bg-blue-600 text-white' : 'bg-gray-200 text-gray-800'
    ]">
      <ng-content></ng-content>
    </button>
  `
})
export class Button {
  @Input() primary = false;
}
```

### Tailwind with Laravel Mix

```js
// webpack.mix.js
const mix = require('laravel-mix');

mix.js('resources/js/app.js', 'public/js')
   .postCss('resources/css/app.css', 'public/css', [
     require('tailwindcss'),
     require('autoprefixer'),
   ]);
```

### Tailwind with Create React App

```bash
npm install -D tailwindcss postcss autoprefixer
npx tailwindcss init
```

Configure content paths for CRA:

```js
module.exports = {
  content: ['./src/**/*.{js,jsx}', './public/index.html'],
  theme: { extend: {} },
  plugins: [],
}
```

### Tailwind with Vite

Vite integrates easily with PostCSS:

```bash
npm install -D tailwindcss postcss autoprefixer
npx tailwindcss init
```

Create `postcss.config.js`:

```js
export default {
  plugins: {
    tailwindcss: {},
    autoprefixer: {},
  },
}
```

Then import Tailwind in your CSS and Vite handles the rest.
